{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93452f74-7924-4048-9876-0eddba6f8468","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Nbw7nV11qQiJzrEHjrKgQN","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_015GWS9LJZM19UcZRYJkTHfU","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-f14e3270c6324f119d9e486ba6167cce && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash for crash dump collection","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash for crash dump collection"}],"interactionId":"0dd9e460-02c7-4e6b-badf-acb122780bb8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run tests and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host process. In .NET, crash dumps can be collected using environment variables:\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` — enables mini dump collection on crash\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` — full dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=<path>` — where to write the dump\n\nOr you can use the `dotnet test` with `--blame-crash` flag which is designed exactly for this purpose — it collects crash dumps when the test host process crashes.\n\n\nThe `--blame-crash` flag is the cleanest approach here, so I'll go with that.","outputTokens":383,"requestId":"CFC5:12531F:153D1C4:18A838A:69EC17AD"},"id":"e03aeb3e-e539-4ef9-b6e1-31e347f0f68f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:24:04.885Z","parentId":"2b9b4111-f057-4edf-ba48-7d48ca9c8231"}
